 from live transcript: live transcript is empty\\\"\\n\\nThe existing code flow:\\n1. `prepare-commit-msg` → checkpoint ID `1f78a5eea34d` added to commit trailer\\n2. `post-commit` → `CondenseSession` → `extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript` → FAILS (empty transcript)\\n3. `condenseAndUpdateState` returns `false` → `handler.condensed = false`\\n4. Line 1017: `if handler.condensed && state.Phase.IsActive()` → FALSE → checkpoint ID NOT recorded in `TurnCheckpointIDs`\\n5. Stop hook → `HandleTurnEnd` → `finalizeAllTurnCheckpoints` → `TurnCheckpointIDs` is empty → no-op\\n6. Result: Commit has `Entire-Checkpoint: 1f78a5eea34d` trailer, but metadata doesn't exist on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n\\nFor the first session, the same flow works because the transcript HAS been flushed by the time the commit fires.\\n\\n## Key Files\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`:\\n  - Line 1017-1018: Where `TurnCheckpointIDs` is populated (only when `handler.condensed`)\\n  - Line 1079-1141: `condenseAndUpdateState` — runs `CondenseSession`, returns true/false\\n  - Line 2123-2262: `HandleTurnEnd` / `finalizeAllTurnCheckpoints` — updates checkpoints with full transcript\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go`:\\n  - Line 103: `CondenseSession` — complex: shadow branches, attribution, summarization\\n  - Line 509-544: `extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript` — returns error when transcript empty\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/committed.go`:\\n  - Line 46: `WriteCommitted` — writes checkpoint to metadata branch\\n  - Line 1113: `UpdateCommitted` — updates existing checkpoint's transcript/prompts\\n  - `ErrCheckpointNotFound` — returned when checkpoint doesn't exist\\n\\n## Approaches I'm Considering\\n\\n### Approach A: Allow empty transcript in extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript\\nChange line 526-528 to use `[]byte(\\\"{}\\\\n\\\")` placeholder instead of returning an error.\\n- Pro: Single-point change, condensation succeeds, finalization replaces placeholder\\n- Con: Checkpoint has placeholder transcript temporarily; what happens if finalization also fails? Metadata (files_touched, attribution) might be wrong/empty since they're derived from the transcript.\\n\\n### Approach B: Record checkpoint ID even on failure + create-or-update in finalization\\n1. At line 1017, also record checkpoint ID when condensation failed (add a new flag like `handler.condenseFailed`)\\n2. In `finalizeAllTurnCheckpoints`, when `UpdateCommitted` returns `ErrCheckpointNotFound`, fall back to calling `CondenseSession` (which now has the full transcript)\\n- Pro: Clean, checkpoint only created when real data is available\\n- Con: Calling `CondenseSession` from finalization context requires: repo, committedFiles, shadow branch info. Some data may not be available. Also need to manage the new flag carefully so carry-forward logic isn't affected.\\n\\n### Approach C: Record checkpoint ID even on failure + simplified WriteCommitted fallback  \\n1. At line 1017, record even on failure\\n2. In `finalizeAllTurnCheckpoints`, when `UpdateCommitted` returns `ErrCheckpointNotFound`, call `WriteCommitted` directly with available data (transcript, prompts, session metadata from state)\\n- Pro: Doesn't need the full CondenseSession machinery\\n- Con: Skips attribution, summarization, and other CondenseSession features\\n\\n## Constraints\\n- The fix should be in `cmd/entire/cli/` (this is a product bug, not a test bug)\\n- Must not break existing behavior for agents that DO flush before committing (Claude Code, etc.)\\n- Must handle the case where the transcript becomes available between post-commit and stop\\n- Should be minimal and focused\\n- Needs unit tests\\n\\n## Questions to Answer\\n1. Which approach is simplest and most correct?\\n2. For Approach B, can we call `CondenseSession` from the finalization context? What data would be missing?\\n3. For Approach A, what metadata would be wrong with a placeholder transcript?\\n4. Is there a simpler hybrid approach?\",\"agentId\":\"a38b2c1a9486f56f9\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"When condensation fails, carry-forward is skipped (line 1027 requires `handler.condensed`). This means `state.FilesTouched` remains the original list, `state.BaseCommit` remains the old commit. The shadow branch is preserved. All of this is correct for the deferred condensation path.\\n\\nBut there's one issue: `state.BaseCommit` is still the old commit after post-commit when condensation failed. At stop time, `CondenseSession` will use the old `BaseCommit` to compute the shadow branch name and find it. But the session state needs to eventually be updated to point to the new HEAD so future sessions work correctly. The deferred `CondenseSession` at stop time should update state the same way `condenseAndUpdateState` does.\\n\\nActually, looking more carefully, `condenseAndUpdateState` (lines 1113-1131) does a lot of state cleanup:\\n- `state.BaseCommit = newHead`\\n- `state.AttributionBaseCommit = newHead`\\n- `state.StepCount = 0`\\n- `state.CheckpointTranscriptStart = result.TotalTranscriptLines`\\n- `state.PromptAttributions = nil`\\n- `state.PendingPromptAttribution = nil`\\n- `state.FilesTouched = nil`\\n- `state.LastCheckpointID = checkpointID`\\n\\nAt stop time, the session is ending anyway, so most of these don't matter. But `CheckpointTranscriptStart` matters if there are multiple deferred checkpoint IDs. And `BaseCommit` matters for shadow branch resolution of subsequent deferred checkpoints.\\n\\nIn the Cursor case (single commit per turn), this isn't a problem. But for correctness, the deferred condensation in `finalizeAllTurnCheckpoints` should update the state similarly.\\n\\nLet me now formalize the complete plan.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Implementation Plan\\n\\n### Approach: Record checkpoint ID on condensation attempt + deferred CondenseSession at stop time\\n\\nThis is Approach B with refinements. It ensures the checkpoint is created with full, correct metadata (att